{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638669"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:57:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:57:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17725"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17725"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76240"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10439"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61744"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5230"},{"type":"tags","id":"5800"},{"type":"tags","id":"10330"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24380"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76240"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old man with chronic lower back pain presents for a medication review. He complains of ongoing dull aching in the lower back and pain with an electric, burning-type quality.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of pain is most appropriately managed with antiseizure medications?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peripheral neuropathic pain","Chronic nociceptive pain","Visceral pain","Psychogenic pain","Acute pain"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral neuropathic pain\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by burning, tingling, or shooting pain due to nerve damage or dysfunction. Antiseizure medications, such as gabapentin and pregabalin, are effective in managing this type of pain by modulating neurotransmitter release and stabilising neuronal membranes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic nociceptive pain\u003C/strong\u003E results from tissue damage or inflammation and is typically managed with analgesics like paracetamol, non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and non-pharmacological therapies. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisceral pain\u003C/strong\u003E originates from internal organs and responds better to antispasmodics or targeted therapy for the underlying condition\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychogenic pain\u003C/strong\u003E requires a multidisciplinary approach focusing on psychological interventions and addressing underlying mental health concerns\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pain\u003C/strong\u003E is typically managed with a mulitmodal approach of analgesics, which can include antiseizure medications like pregabalin although they are not the mainstay of treatment. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntiseizure medications are particularly effective for neuropathic pain because they reduce neuronal hyperexcitability and abnormal firing patterns that contribute to this type of pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antiseizure medications are effective first-line treatments for peripheral neuropathic pain by stabilising hyperexcitable nerve membranes.","Neuropathic pain typically presents with burning, electric shock-like, or shooting qualities","Antiseizure medications can play a role in acute pain management in specific circumstances, but are not used first-line"],"references":["Jensen TS. Anticonvulsants in neuropathic pain: rationale and clinical evidence. Eur J Pain. 2002;6 Suppl A:61-8. doi: 10.1053/eujp.2001.0324. PMID: 11888243.","Tremont-Lukats IW, Megeff C, Backonja MM. Anticonvulsants for neuropathic pain syndromes: mechanisms of action and place in therapy. Drugs. 2000 Nov;60(5):1029-52. doi: 10.2165/00003495-200060050-00005. PMID: 11129121."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61744"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17725"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61744"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T15:12:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T15:13:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10439"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76240"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app